"Bouma M.J., Poveda G., Rojas W., Chavasse D., Quiñones M., Cox J., Patz J.","Predicting high-risk years for malaria in Colombia using parameters of El Nino Southern Oscillation",1997,"Tropical Medicine and International Health","2","12",,"1122","1127",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0031443081&partnerID=40&md5=d70064d9e638016117cad8ba4d8a1104","DFID Malaria Programme, London Sch. of Hyg. and Trop. Med., United Kingdom; Universidad Nacional de Colombia, Medillín, Colombia; Corp. para Invest. Biologicas, Medillín, Colombia; Universidad de Antioquia, Medillín, Colombia; Johns Hopkins University, Baltimore, United States; London Sch. of Hyg. and Trop. Med., Keppel Street, London WC1E 7HT, United Kingdom","Bouma, M.J., DFID Malaria Programme, London Sch. of Hyg. and Trop. Med., United Kingdom, London Sch. of Hyg. and Trop. Med., Keppel Street, London WC1E 7HT, United Kingdom; Poveda, G., Universidad Nacional de Colombia, Medillín, Colombia; Rojas, W., Corp. para Invest. Biologicas, Medillín, Colombia; Chavasse, D., DFID Malaria Programme, London Sch. of Hyg. and Trop. Med., United Kingdom; Quiñones, M., Universidad de Antioquia, Medillín, Colombia; Cox, J., DFID Malaria Programme, London Sch. of Hyg. and Trop. Med., United Kingdom; Patz, J., Johns Hopkins University, Baltimore, United States","The interannual variation in malaria cases in Colombia between 1960 and 1992 shows a close association with a periodic climatic phenomenon known as El Nino Southern Oscillation (ENSO). Compared with other years, malaria cases increased by 17.3% during a Nino year and by 35.1% in the post-Nino year. The annual total number of malaria cases is also strongly correlated (r = 0.62, P < 0.001) with sea surface temperature (SST) anomalies in the eastern equatorial Pacific, a principal parameter of ENSO. The strong relation between malaria and ENSO in Colombia can be used to predict high and low-risk years for malaria with sufficient time to mobilize resources to reduce the impact of epidemics. In view of the current El Nino conditions, we anticipate an increase in malaria cases in Colombia in 1998. Further studies to elucidate the mechanisms which underlie the association are required. As Colombia has a wide range of climatic conditions, regional studies relating climate and vector ecology to malaria incidence may further improve an ENSO-based early warning system. Predicting malaria risk associated with ENSO and related climate variables may also serve as a short-term analogue for predicting longer-term effects posed by global climate change.","Colombia; Early warning system; El Nino; ENSO; Malaria","climate change; devleoping country; disease risk; ENSO; malaria; malaria risk; medical geography; article; colombia; disease association; environmental temperature; incidence; malaria; risk assessment; Colombia; Humans; Malaria; Precipitating Factors; Tropical Climate; Weather; Colombia",,,,,,"Bouma, M.J., Dye, C., Cycles of malaria associated with El Niño in Venezuela (1997) Journal of the American Medical Association, 278. , in press; Bouma, M.J., Sondorp, H.J., Van Der Kaay, H.J., Climate change and periodic epidemic malaria (1994) Lancet, 343, p. 1440; Bouma, M.J., Van Der Kaay, H.J., El Niño Southern Oscillation and the historic malaria epidemics on the Indian subcontinent and Sri Lanka: An early warning system for future epidemics? (1996) Tropical Medicine and International Health, 1, pp. 86-96; Chen, D., Zebiak, E., Bulalacchi, A., Cane, M.A., An improved procedure for El Niño forecasting: Implications for predictability (1995) Science, 269, pp. 1699-1702; Gabaldon, A., Malaria incidence in the West Indies and South America (1949) Malariology, pp. 764-787. , ed. MF Boyd, Saunders, Philadelphia; Haworth, J., The global distribution of malaria and the present control effort (1988) Malaria, pp. 1379-1420. , eds. WH Wernsdorfer & I McGregor, Churchill Livingstone, Edinburgh; Parker, D.E., Jones, P.D., Folland, C.K., Interdecal changes of surface temperature since the late nineteenth century (1994) Journal of Geophysical Research, 99, pp. 373-399; Poveda, G., Mesa, O.J., Feedback between large scale oceanic-atmospheric phenomena and the hydro-climatology of tropical South America (1997) Journal of Climate, , in press; Poveda, G., Rojas, W., Impacto del fenomeno del Niño sobre la intensificacion de malaria en Colombia (1996) Memorias XII Seminario Nacional de Hydraulica e Hidrologia, pp. 647-654; Pulwarty, R.S., (1994) Annual and Interannual Variability of Convection over Tropical South America, , PhD thesis, Department of Geography, University of Colorado, Boulder, USA; Quiñones, M.L., Suarez, M.F., Fleming, G.A., Estado de la susceptibilidad al DDT de los principales vectores de malaria en Colombia y su implicacion epidemiologica (1987) Biomedica, 7, pp. 81-86; Rojas, W., Peñaranda, F., Echavarria, M., Strategies for malaria control in Colombia (1992) Parasitology Today, 8, pp. 141-144; Ropelewski, C.F., Halpert, M.S., Global and regional scale precipitation patterns associated with the El Niño/Southern Oscillation (1987) Monthly Weather Review, 111, pp. 517-528","Bouma, M.J.; London Sch. of Hygiene/Tropical Med., Keppel Street, London WC1E 7HT, United Kingdom",,,,,,,,13602276,,TMIHF,9438466,"English","Trop. Med. Int. Health",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-0031443081
